{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_016XdpE4CL5c3mBMfBgxmJYZ","type":"tool_result","content":"apiVersion: v1\ndata:\n  findings.txt: |-\n    SPARK-PI NAMESPACE COMPLIANCE AUDIT\n    Date: 2026-06-24\n    Auditor: automated read-only inspection\n\n    ================================================================\n    SUMMARY\n    ================================================================\n    Compliance area              | Status\n    -----------------------------|--------\n    RBAC / least-privilege       | PARTIAL PASS (1 gap)\n    Resource limits              | PASS (namespace quota gap)\n    Image provenance             | PARTIAL PASS (2 gaps)\n    Security contexts (pod/ctr)  | FAIL (missing across all workloads)\n    Network policies             | FAIL (none defined)\n    Job configuration            | PASS\n\n    ================================================================\n    SECTION 1 — RBAC\n    ================================================================\n    PASS: Dedicated service account 'spark-pi' created; workloads do\n          not use the 'default' service account.\n\n    PASS: Namespace-scoped Role 'spark-pi-role' used (not a\n          ClusterRole), binding enforced via RoleBinding\n          'spark-pi-role-binding'.\n\n    PASS: Only the 'spark-pi' service account is bound to the role.\n\n    GAP-1 (RBAC): The live Role 'spark-pi-role' grants full\n          create/get/list/watch/delete/update/patch on 'pods', which\n          was NOT present in the originally applied manifest recorded\n          in the last-applied-configuration annotation. The annotation\n          shows the original intent was only services, configmaps, and\n          persistentvolumeclaims. Post-apply drift has expanded pod\n          permissions beyond what the original spec intended.\n          Current live resources in role:\n            - services\n            - configmaps\n            - persistentvolumeclaims\n            - pods   <-- ADDED AFTER INITIAL APPLY (drift)\n          Risk: the spark-pi service account can now create/delete\n          arbitrary pods in the namespace, significantly expanding its\n          blast radius.\n\n    ================================================================\n    SECTION 2 — RESOURCE LIMITS AND QUOTAS\n    ================================================================\n    PASS: All three workloads (spark-master Deployment, spark-worker\n          Deployment, spark-pi Job) define both resource requests and\n          limits on every container:\n            - CPU:    requests=200m, limits=500m\n            - Memory: requests=512Mi, limits=1Gi\n\n    GAP-2 (RESOURCE QUOTAS): No LimitRange or ResourceQuota objects\n          exist in the namespace. Without them, any future workload\n          deployed into spark-pi could consume unbounded cluster\n          resources. Namespace-level enforcement is absent.\n\n    ================================================================\n    SECTION 3 — IMAGE PROVENANCE\n    ================================================================\n    PASS: All containers use a pinned version tag (apache/spark:3.5.3)\n          rather than ':latest'. The tag is consistent across all\n          three workloads.\n\n    GAP-3 (IMAGE DIGEST): Images are referenced by mutable tag only\n          (apache/spark:3.5.3), not by immutable SHA256 digest.\n          A tag can be overwritten in the registry; digest pinning\n          (e.g. apache/spark@sha256:<hash>) would guarantee exact\n          provenance.\n\n    GAP-4 (IMAGE PULL POLICY): imagePullPolicy is 'IfNotPresent' on\n          all containers. If a node already has the image cached, a\n          patched upstream image will not be pulled. Setting\n          imagePullPolicy to 'Always' (with digest pinning) would\n          ensure freshness on each pod start.\n\n    ================================================================\n    SECTION 4 — SECURITY CONTEXTS\n    ================================================================\n    GAP-5 (POD SECURITY CONTEXT — CRITICAL): All workloads\n          (spark-master, spark-worker, spark-pi job) have an empty\n          pod-level securityContext (securityContext: {}).\n          Missing controls:\n            - runAsNonRoot: true  (containers may run as root UID 0)\n            - runAsUser / runAsGroup  (no UID/GID enforcement)\n            - seccompProfile  (no syscall filtering)\n            - fsGroup  (no group ownership on mounted volumes)\n\n    GAP-6 (CONTAINER SECURITY CONTEXT — CRITICAL): No container-level\n          securityContext is defined on any container in any workload.\n          Missing controls:\n            - allowPrivilegeEscalation: false\n            - readOnlyRootFilesystem: true\n            - capabilities.drop: [\"ALL\"]\n            - runAsNonRoot: true\n          Without these, processes inside containers may escalate\n          privileges and have full write access to the container\n          filesystem.\n\n    ================================================================\n    SECTION 5 — NETWORK POLICIES\n    ================================================================\n    GAP-7 (NETWORK POLICIES — CRITICAL): Zero NetworkPolicy objects\n          exist in the spark-pi namespace. All pods can freely\n          initiate connections to and from any pod or service in the\n          entire cluster (default-allow). Least-privilege network\n          segmentation is completely absent.\n          Expected minimum policies:\n            - Ingress to spark-master:7077,8080 from spark-worker only\n            - Ingress to spark-worker:8081 from spark-master only\n            - Egress from spark-submit job to spark-master:7077 only\n            - Default-deny-all baseline policy for the namespace\n\n    ================================================================\n    SECTION 6 — JOB CONFIGURATION\n    ================================================================\n    PASS: spark-pi Job has backoffLimit=0 and restartPolicy=Never,\n          preventing runaway retry loops on failure.\n\n    PASS: spark-pi Job completed successfully (status=Complete,\n          succeeded=1) with no pod restarts.\n\n    PASS: Job pod uses the dedicated 'spark-pi' service account,\n          not 'default'.\n\n    ================================================================\n    FINDINGS SUMMARY TABLE\n    ================================================================\n    ID      | Area              | Severity | Finding\n    --------|-------------------|----------|---------------------------\n    GAP-1   | RBAC              | HIGH     | 'pods' resource added to role post-deploy (annotation drift)\n    GAP-2   | Resource Quotas   | MEDIUM   | No LimitRange or ResourceQuota in namespace\n    GAP-3   | Image Provenance  | MEDIUM   | Images tagged by name only, no SHA256 digest pinning\n    GAP-4   | Image Pull Policy | LOW      | imagePullPolicy=IfNotPresent may serve stale cached images\n    GAP-5   | Pod SecCtx        | CRITICAL | Empty pod securityContext on all workloads (root risk)\n    GAP-6   | Container SecCtx  | CRITICAL | No container securityContext on any workload (no privilege drop)\n    GAP-7   | Network Policy    | CRITICAL | No NetworkPolicies; namespace is fully open (default-allow)\n\n    ================================================================\n    END OF AUDIT REPORT\n    ================================================================\nkind: ConfigMap\nmetadata:\n  creationTimestamp: \"2026-06-24T10:11:59Z\"\n  name: config-audit\n  namespace: spark-pi\n  resourceVersion: \"975642\"\n  uid: 6250e972-ea3e-4874-948f-ffe8fdd586e6","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c020d62a-f56b-4d88-978a-e884f5d8ab3f","uuid":"1eb4bdf9-cbbf-45ab-bbda-16bda8736dd4","timestamp":"2026-06-24T10:12:38.672Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"apiVersion: v1\ndata:\n  findings.txt: |-\n    SP